The deadline to pre order free meals for children age 1-18 is 5 p.m. tonight. Here are the details sent via email and text Monday.

Pre-order meals for week of Sept. 21-25

Free meals (breakfast/lunch combo) are available for children for the week of Sept. 21-25. Here are the options available.

3 days of free meals for students on a Blue or Gold schedule for when they are not in school
5 days of free meals for students in the Kuna Online Only Program
5 days of free meals for children (age 1-18) not enrolled in the Kuna School District (KSD)

Please use this link to pre-order meals: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/KSDMeals92125
At the end of the form, you will choose your pick up time on Friday, Sept. 18.

9.2.2020 Sports Update: Kuna Parents

We are excited to share that the West Ada School Board last night approved a return to competition for their high school sports teams.

This means our athletes will have some teams to play. Because the spread of COVID in our county remains in ‚Äúred‚Äù West Ada, like Kuna, the limit on large group gatherings remains.

This means no spectators here and in West Ada. West Ada also is using the NFHS Network to livestream some games: https://www.nfhsnetwork.com/

Here is the schedule of activities this week:

Wednesday: JV/V Girls Soccer @ Rocky Mountain 5:30 and 7 pm
Thursday: Soph/JV/V Volleyball @ Centennial 4:30, 5:30, 6:30 pm
Thursday: JV/V Boys Soccer vs. Rocky Mountain 4:30, 6:00 pm
Thursday: JV Football vs. Eagle JV 6 pm
Thursday: Frosh Football @ Eagle Frosh. 6 pm
Friday: V Football Kuna @ Eagle 7 pm

We are so excited that our students will be able to play during this time!

post_text:
reminder about how to watch the games today:

Central District Health Department‚Äôs limit on gatherings of 10 or less means no tailgate parties or spectators at today's KHS junior varsity and varsity football games against Lewiston.

Anyone can watch the game -- for a fee -- through the NFHS (Pixellot) streaming service: https://www.nfhsnetwork.com/schools/kuna-high-school-kuna-id

NFHS does not offer a single game option. Instead for $10.99, the subscriber gets access to a month of streaming service. (Annual plans also are available) This service includes all sports that are streamed by our district AND the subscriber can watch games streamed by other districts including many in the Treasure Valley.

Updated Bell Schedule: Only change Fremont Middle School end time. The many road construction projects will impact our bus routes and pick up and drop off times. Please be patient as we navigate these projects, adapt routes, and change times as needed. The best source of information is the transportation website: http://www.kunaschools.org/index.php/transportation As our team works to identify afternoon drop off times, please keep in mind our goal is for drop offs to occur no later than an hour after leaving the school.

Projects include:
Kuna Road from Black Cat to Ten Mile through 9/18/2020
Deer Flat from Linder to Massey through 9/11/2020
Linder & Deer Flat intersection through 10/23/2020
Main St Ave A to Ave D (lane restrictions) through 9/13/2020

post_text: **Updated with information about afternoon drop off ** Bus stops are posted! Please note: Routes and stops do change as we adapt to accommodate growth and construction. The page includes a note on when information was last updated. The expectation is afternoon drop off is no later than 1 hour. We are working to get more precise times after drivers return and begin to drive routes and we understand the impact of the various road construction projects. Please be patient. To help prevent the spread of the virus and reduce the number of riders on a bus, we encourage families to have students to walk or bike to school if it is safe to do so. Riders are required to wear face coverings on the bus. Buses will be cleaned before and after routes. http://www.kunaschools.org/index.php/transportation

post_text: Update on middle school schedules.
shared_text:
Fremont Middle School
August 11 at 8:43 PM ¬∑

Good afternoon Everyone,

We‚Äôve had many inquiries about schedules. Due to circumstances created by the coronavirus (shifting teachers to online school, budget constraints, transferring teachers to other placements), schedules should be available to view online by August 27th. We appreciate your understanding and flexibility. Also, we are not able to honor requests (beyond extenuating circumstances) to switch from Blue to Gold or vice versa nor are we able to honor requests for open enrollment due to our current uncertain situation. Once school begins in-person, we can re-evaluate the Gold/Blue enrollments and open enrollment requests and make determinations at that time. Again, thank you for your understanding.

Mr. Jensen, FMS Principal, Middle School Coordinator
Mr. Souza, KMS Principal

Due to circumstances created by the coronavirus (shifting teachers to online school, budget constraints, transferring teachers to other placements), schedules should be available to view online by August 27th. We appreciate your understanding and flexibility. Also, we are not able to honor requests (beyond extenuating circumstances) to switch from Blue to Gold or vice versa nor are we able to honor requests for open enrollment due to our current uncertain situation. Once school begins in-person, we can re-evaluate the Gold/Blue enrollments and open enrollment requests and make determinations at that time. Again, thank you for your understanding.

Mr. Jensen, FMS Principal, Middle School Coordinator
Mr. Souza, KMS Principal

KHS Alumni Spotlight
2016 KHS graduate Annalise Burke recently graduated with honors from Rutgers College. When asked how KHS prepared her for future success this is what she told us.

‚ÄúWhile at KHS, I was the President of Business Professionals of America and participated in the High School of Business program. As a Public Policy and Korean double major at Rutgers, I found the concepts learned through those KHS activities gave me an edge in courses such as Policy Economics, Statistics for Policy Research, and Federal Taxation. Additionally, participation in BPA prepared me for competition on a national level for college admissions. Currently, I am preparing for my fourth U.S. State Department-funded program, this time as a Fulbright ETA Scholar in South Korea.‚Äù
Congratulations to Annalise!

April 20 at 11:55 PM ¬∑

Kuna Healthcare is now testing for both active and antibody testing of the COVID-19 virus. If you are interested, PLEASE CALL the office to set up the appointment. We are not scheduling these tests online.

The cost for the test is $45.00. If you are having active symptoms, insurance may cover it. However, if you are more interested in the antibody testing, the insurance coverage is unclear at this time and can be paid for by the patient at the time of visit. The COVID test is a blood draw, not a swab.

post_text:
Secondary spring sports fees update

On Tuesday, the Kuna Board of Trustees authorized us to reach out to families with options for fees paid for spring sports and activities that were cancelled.

Schools will contact families of middle and high school students who purchased an Associated Student Body card and paid participation fees after Feb. 1, 2020.

Families may opt to apply the fee to next year, be reimbursed, or donate the fee.

Please do not respond to this post with your choice!

Look for more information soon from district activities director Tracy Donaldson or your student's school.

post_text:
Watch Gov. Little‚Äôs news conference and get the facts about Idaho‚Äôs first COVID-19 case.

The Governor continues to reiterate that schools do not need to close at this time. Officials are not recommending Idaho schools close at this time: ‚ÄúNew guidance from the CDC today was actually that schools practice more of hand washing and those practical matters at this time. They are urging schools, rather than close for Idaho, they are urging us and across the nation to just talk to kids about hand washing and hygiene like we are with adults.‚Äù

The Centers for Disease Control also said: "Closing schools early in the spread of disease for a short time (e.g., 2 weeks) will be unlikely to stem the spread of disease or prevent impact on the health care system, while causing significant disruption for families, schools, and those who may be responding to COVID-19 outbreaks in health care settings. It may also increase impact on older adults who care for grandchildren."
